#let images = (
  "table-9-1": (
    caption: [Grades of Organization in Organismal Complexity. 1. Protoplasmic grade: unicellular organisms. 2. Cellular grade: aggregation of functionally differentiated cells (e.g., Volvox, sponges). 3. Cell-tissue grade: aggregation of similar cells into tissues (e.g., Cnidaria). 4. Tissue-organ grade: aggregation of tissues into organs (e.g., Platyhelminthes). 5. Organ-system grade: organs work together to perform functions (e.g., Nemertean worms and most animal phyla).],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-47-53.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-1": (
    caption: [Animal symmetry. Illustrated are animals showing spherical, radial, and bilateral symmetry. Spherical symmetry divides body into mirrored halves by any plane through center. Radial symmetry divides body into similar halves by more than two planes through longitudinal axis. Bilateral symmetry divides body into right and left halves by a sagittal plane.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-48-28.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-2": (
    caption: [The planes of symmetry as illustrated by a bilaterally symmetrical animal. Anterior (head), posterior (tail), dorsal (back), ventral (belly). Frontal plane divides into dorsal/ventral. Sagittal plane divides into right/left. Transverse plane (cross section) divides into anterior/posterior.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-50-36.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-3": (
    caption: [Mesoderm formation and body plans. A: Protostomes. Mesoderm forms from endodermal cells near blastopore. Acoelomate: mesoderm fills blastocoel. Pseudocoelomate: mesoderm lines outer edge of blastocoel. Schizocoelous: mesodermal band splits to form coelom. B: Deuterostomes (Enterocoelous plan). Mesoderm forms as pouches from gut lining, which pinch off to form coelom.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-51-00.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-4": (
    caption: [Acoelomate, pseudocoelomate, and eucoelomate body plans shown as cross sections. Acoelomate: parenchyma fills space between gut and epidermis. Pseudocoelomate: pseudocoelom (persistent blastocoel) exists between gut and mesoderm. Eucoelomate: coelom is completely lined by mesodermal peritoneum; mesenteries suspend organs.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-51-46.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-5": (
    caption: [Developmental sequences in animals. Diploblastic: 2 germ layers (e.g., Cnidaria). Triploblastic: 3 germ layers. Triploblasts divide into Protostomes (spiral cleavage, mosaic, blastopore becomes mouth, schizocoely) and Deuterostomes (radial cleavage, regulative, blastopore becomes anus, enterocoely). Protostomes further split into Lophotrochozoans and Ecdysozoans.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-53-07.png"
  ),
  "figure-9-6": (
    caption: [Segmented phyla. Segmentation (metamerism) is the serial repetition of similar body segments (metameres/somites). Examples: Annelida (earthworms), Arthropoda (insects, crabs), and Chordata (vertebrates). Segmentation allows for greater mobility and specialization.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-11-19-16-53-42.png"
  ),
